Keeping in mind the most recent studies about omicron being 2x more transmissible than delta covid variant: delta first appeared in US in March 2021 and reached 50% of covid cases by July 3rd 2021 (roughly 4 months to 50% of covid cases). If omicron is 2x more transmissible than delta (and using delta’s doubling rate as a model), the estimated time to 70% of cases being omicron is ~mid march. However, reports in UK and Denmark state the doubling rate of omicron variant cases is 2.5 days, with an estimate of 50% of covid cases consisting of omicron variant within the next two to four weeks (as of Dec 9, so by January 9th). First case was found Nov 27th (UK) and Dec 1 (US).

Perhaps they also don’t have a holiday reporting problem like the US does (?), although this lag in reporting seems less relevant because the bin boundary is Jan. 15 and there should be plenty of time to record/report an extremely large wave in the US if it has already expressed before then. My bin #4 probability represents scenarios where differences stated above cause a “flattening of the curve” in the US, and the Omicron tidal wave comes several weeks later than expected.

In the UK, Omicron prevalence in sequence data was ~1.44% on Nov 28, with the prevalence doubling just under 3 days. If we were to take a similar prevalence in the US, Omicron would be ~6% of all cases in the US. That's probably an overestimate, but perhaps not by much, as one can see that "Other" sequences have bumped up by maybe <5% very recently, albeit with extremely small numbers and great uncertainty: https://outbreak.info/location-reports?loc=USA Suppose one conservatively estimates that Omicron currently causes, say, 4% of US cases. Then Omicron could be dominant in the US soon after the middle of the month -- depending on what Delta does nearly independently of Omicron. But there are signs that Delta cases may be turning downwards, even as we head into peak Covid season, and that makes bin 3 look more likely to me, with the 2 weeks ending Jan 15 most likely, but the 2 weeks ending Jan 1 also slightly possible. I'm certain that Omicron will reach >70% and will do so in the near future because its competition isn't even close in terms of both the % of the population that is susceptible and its ability to spread, which is just shy of that of chickenpox.

When Delta and antigenically similar strains die down, Omicron will have the advantage. And no other strain to date has the same advantage of near-complete-to-complete escape of neutralizing antibodies. When will Delta and antigenically similar variants die down? When they do, I suspect Omicron will quickly reach >70.0% of all cases. I am curious why some of you put ≥50% weight on bin 5. Is it because you are not confident that Omicron will spread, or because you are not confident that it will be able to reach >70.0% because multiple variants may be spreading, or both?

I think it would be very difficult for any variant to overtake Delta in the CDC data (which would require >70.0% of all sequences in a 2-week period to be of a non-Delta lineage) by Jan 15. Omicron or whatever would need to go from 0% to 70% in 6 weeks. If Delta continues to surge through early January, that's not going to happen. Otoh, if Delta winds down this month, it's still possible. However, I don't think it's likely that Delta will wind down to low levels by the end of December; I suspect it'll still be going at least fairly strong and will likely peak in early January, like last year. So, I think bin 3 has a very low probability. Bin 4 is much more likely, imo. But when Delta winds down, more than one variant may arise at the same time. Omicron will likely spread regardless of what Delta is doing and will likely co-circulate just fine; I don't think it will "replace" Delta in any meaningful way. Other variants that escape more or less existing antibody immunity may also start to be visible by bin 4. It's likely that one will do better than the rest, but by how much? I think it's a near certainty that Delta will represent <50% of cases by sometime in bin 4, but it's not clear yet whether one variant will emerge to cause >70.0% of all cases.

The Nu variant, also known as B.1.1.529, is quite concerning. A couple other variants are, too, but Nu seems to be the worst by far. We need more data to know what this variant is capable of, but the data so far are extremely concerning. While it is important not to jump to very firm conclusions without more data, there is enough data to cause a lot of worry, and South African health professionals are telling us to be very concerned. It's also important to remember that many downplayed Delta early on because "we didn't have enough data," when Indian health professionals told us to be concerned; we don't need to be able to draw firm conclusions to be very concerned. A number of Nu cases have so far been identified in vaccinated people. There is a lot of selection bias in the detection of these cases, though, so it will be important to see how well Nu spreads in the vaccinated and previously infected as time goes on. Delta was dominant in India by mid-March and peaked in early May, and it became dominant in the US by mid-July and peaked in early Sept. Thus, it is conceivable to me that a variant that supersedes Delta to become dominant in SA at the end of November could spread to and within countries faster than Delta did and could become dominant in the US by mid March. Also, note that it's possible that this variant may already be spreading at higher or similar numbers in countries other than SA. It may simply have been detected first in SA because of greater surveillance and because it is causing a surge on top of a very low baseline of Delta cases. In other countries, particularly those with greater Delta spread and/or little surveillance, it could easily go undetected for quite a while. It has been detected almost simultaneously in travelers from SA, Malawi and Egypt, once people started to look. It may be spreading fairly widely within several or many countries in Africa and has likely already spread in small numbers, undetected, to many or most countries around the world. Also, note that it has now been shown conclusively that a new variant can become dominant in a region with low spread; no giant surge is required when a region has a low starting point. https://twitter.com/ariehkovler/status/1464194918038093825

At this point, I now assess the chances of this question's conditions being met prior to 12 March 2022 at less than 0.5%, so I am assigning a forecast that looks like "full certainty". However, my forecast wouldn't yet be 100% on the final bin if we were able to specify probabilities more precisely at the very high/low end of the probability scale. (The average American's probability of being in a car accident next year surely far exceeds the probability of them winning the lottery (if they play), and yet both of those meaningfully distinguishable, non-zero probabilities should presumably be most accurately represented in the GJO format as a "0% / 100%" yes/no forecast.)

I do not see a strong likelihood that a new potent strain will represent new Covid infections before March of 2022. The height of the Delta outbreak in India took place in December of 2020 (if was first discovered in Oct of that same year). The impact of that outbreak on the US started in May. We are still in the midst of a "Delta surge" at the moment.

Delta is sweeping the world, and SARSCoV2 variants are undergoing a selective sweep by Delta. As I've thought more about this, I'm thinking that the rival natural of these variants is important. It makes the question harder because there is dependence. For example, Delta decreasing while another strand increases (in nominal values) seems less likely than first glance - as both variants seek the same conditions for transmission. Therefore, new strand is only likely to exceed the growth rate of Delta if it is more contagious than Delta. The most likely way for that to happen is to be resistant against Delta while being susceptible to another strand. That requires two conditions - immunity and mutation, followed by spread. Therefore, I'm further reducing the near-term bins, but remaining uneasy about the potential for a new strand to spread in the Winter after Delta immunity is greatly increased by the Fall.

Revising bin 2 downward. Also, given that we've only seen ancestral strains and Delta reach >70% since the pandemic started, it could be most reasonable to weight the last bin very high. But variants arise by the stochastic process of genetic mutation and then are selected for or against by their environment. Right now, immunity throughout the world as a whole is low enough that increased transmissibility is the dominant feature that is selected for; immune escape seems to be less important to the virus at the moment. So we can estimate that the chance of formation of new, highly transmissible variants is proportional to the number of cases in the world at any given time. Now that Delta is making its way through many places, we may start to see a peak in cases in the Norther Hemisphere Winter and a peak in the Southern Hemisphere winter. There could be peaks outside these periods if a highly contagious variant starts to spread uncontrolled in an immunologically naive population like that of China, or if a drastic immune-escape variant develops. But I'm going to hypothesize that N and S winters are going to present the greatest risk of generating new variants of relevance to this question and that these variants could spread to the US soon after generation.

There were roughly 2 months between Alpha becoming dominant and Delta becoming dominant. So, it would be reasonable to guess that it could be another 2 to 4 months until another strain becomes dominant. But when *one* strain represents more than *70%* of cases is another question. Also, it's quite possible that the next strain to become dominant in the US could be an immune-escape Delta sublineage, although the world is certainly busy brewing up a lot of other options, including Lambda. It will take a new variant that reaches values of Rt (like R0, but varies over time) greater than those of all others that are circulating to get to 70%. Delta still has no real competition that we know of, so I think bin 1 is almost out of the question. But I think the rest of the field is wide open. I'm weighting bin 3 high because the Northern Hemisphere can expect a winter peak as early as January, depending on mitigations, so there will be a lot of opportunities for new strains to spread.
